axpayer money.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Union Carbide Corp. agreed to pay $470million to the government of India in a surprise court-orderedsettlement resulting from the 1984 gas leak at Bhopal that killedmore than 3,300 people in the world's worst industrial disaster.   Activists in Bhopal denounced Tuesday's settlement as a betrayalof the 20,000 victims who still suffer from exposure to the deadlygas that escaped from a pesticides plant on Dec. 3, 1984.   The government had sought $3 billion in damages.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   General Motors Corp. said its fourth-quarterprofit soared 67.5 percent from a year earlier and that it postedrecord earnings for all of 1988.   GM's earnings, reported Tuesday, mean the nation's biggestautomaker will issue $114 million in profit-sharing checks to some470,000 hourly employees, the first such payments since fiscal 1985.   In the three months ended Dec. 31, GM had net income of $1.4billion, or $4.25 a share, up from $835.8 million, or $2.36 a share,in the same period of 1987. Revenue during the quarter rose to $32.4billion from $29.7 billion a year earlier.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chicago Board of Trade Chairman Karsten Mahlmannsaid he was not personally involved in his trading firm's hiringlast year of two men who have since been indicted on federal fraudcharges.   The two salesmen, Michael N. Kolb and Jan Y. Biesiadecki, wereindicted by a federal grand jury Jan. 17 on charges they defraudedinvestors while working for First Commodity Corp. of Boston, afutures brokerage that collapsed in 1986 after its expulsion fromthe MidAmerica Commodity Exchange, a Board of Trade affiliate.   Mahlmann said Tuesday that he had not been involved withindividual hirings over the past two years.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Threatened with a possible strike March 3 bymilitant machinists, Eastern Airlines has introduced ``SuperCoupons'' offering passengers sizable discounts if they fly afterthat date.   Some analysts and travel agents said Tuesday that the coupons,offered during the peak winter travel period, marked a desperatemove by the strapped airline.</TEXT><DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   USX Corp. and Kobe Steel Ltd. of Japanannounced a joint venture to operate USX's plant in Lorain, Ohio.   Kobe, the last of Japan's big integrated steelmakers to join witha comparable U.S. producer, said Tuesday it will pay an undisclosedsum to buy half the plant.   The deal leaves only Bethlehem Steel Corp., the third-largestU.S. producer, without a partner from the Far East.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   The stock market turned in an indecisive showing Tuesday afterrising interest rates helped blunt an early advance. The Dow Jonesaverage of 30 industrials closed with a 1.25 point loss at 2,281.25.   The dollar dropped against most major currencies. Gold priceswere mixed.   Bond prices finished lower, pulled down by a sagging dollar inworld currency trading.   Soybean and corn futures rose sharply; cattle futures were mostlylower; pork mostly was higher; precious metals were mixed and energyfutures mostly declined.</TEXT></DOC>